I think it's critical to look at the math logic, but then step back and say, oh wait, where is it occurring? It is occurring now. No matter how correct or incorrect the logic is, the logic occurs now, it is subject to now, and it is bound by now.

Non-SR is like trying to apply the math logic to yourself, but not realizing it occurs now. Like calculating yourself in the past/future, you can see that you can predict things tomorrow, and that you can use the past to predict things in the present moment, but the central entity which past and future occurs to is never actually seen, ever, because, again if you step back, the logic is always bound by now. Logic does not occur in past or future, it occurs now. 

Our self-knowledge is like reading a book. You are always reading, now. A book can describe the past, but you are reading it now. A book can describe the future, but you are reading it now. SR is like realizing that you are always reading now, therefore the book isn't describing anything.

This seems very intellectual and reductionist, which reminds me of how I previously inquired.

It's not that you're wrong. But it seems like you're trying to boil experience down to some kind of substance or logic. And while it's not wrong or right, it perpetuates this imperative of "I need to understand something, I need to be something, I need to become more knowledgeable about my experience, etc." And that imperative was the biggest obstacle for me personally. It's less about being correct or knowledgable, more about realizing that being correct and knowledgable is always subject to what is only occurring ***now.*** And so that is what would be meant by "looking at the limitations of thought/knowledge."

If you zoom out, and look at it, the entirety of experience is occurring now. So the notion of "me understanding" is actually an extrapolation into time, because it relates to someone who will gain some understanding in the future which you do not have ***now.*** There is no moment in the future where you will understand something or something will change, there is just this moment now which is what you will always be, so stop thinking about past and future enhancements about yourself.

Understanding that you are always yourself now, and there is no future you can jump into in order to gain knowledge about yourself, should show you that there isn't any object in knowledge "occurring later" which could illuminate what you are, because every single thing that exists is encapsulated in ***now,*** not past or future.

TLDR, my suggestion, focus on the implications of "now."

The object is physically limited to what is occurring "now", always, no matter what. It doesn't matter how many elaborate "yesterdays" and "tomorrows" it conjures up about you, it must always display them **now **because everything has always occurred **now.** There is only "displaying now", there is no such thing as "displaying in the past" or "displaying in the future."

The past and future only exist relative to the vantage point of now. All knowledge about past occurs now, and therefore knowledge about the past never occurs to you. All knowledge about future occurs now, therefore knowledge about the future never occurs to you.

The vantage point is always now, no matter what. To see the past, you have to be in the now. To see the future, you have to be in the now. There's no such thing as a past while being in the past, or else you are simply in the present. There's no such thing as a future while being in the future, or else you are simply in the present. 

There is no difference between someone who only experiences the past, someone who only experiences the future, and someone who only experiences now; there is no difference between any of those periods of time. Thoughts don't thread time together.

There is just thinking, now. It is always thinking, now. It is always knowledge, now.

That's really good.

Hypothetically, say there was a physical device which displayed knowledge.

If you tasked it with remembering what you ate yesterday, it would display a memory of that.

If you tasked it with deciding what to eat in the future, it displays a picture of lasagna, and then says "I want to eat that."

Then let's say you tasked it with displaying what "you" are.

It could not refer to the past, because whatever it displays is going to occur now, not in the past. Therefore nothing from the past ever occurs to you. The object can't display something that occurs in the past. It only display the past, now.

It could not refer to the future, because whatever it displays is going to occur now, not in the future. Therefore nothing from the future ever occurs to you. The object can't display something that occurs in the future. It can only display the future, now.

To elaborate:

Say it displays a memory of yourself from yesterday. That memory is being displayed now by the object, therefore yesterday is never actually experienced by you.

Say it displays a video of what you will do tomorrow. That video is being displayed now by the object, therefore tomorrow is never actually experienced by you.

Thinking back, you've never experienced yesterday or tomorrow. You have experienced yourself, **right now**, thinking about yesterday and tomorrow, from what is physically happening **right now.**

Tomorrow by definition is a projection from now. Yesterday by definition is a projection from now. There is no such thing as thinking about tomorrow from tomorrow. There is no such thing as thinking about yesterday from yesterday.

There are simply thoughts about yourself which feel a certain way.

There are perhaps environmental stimuli which trigger certain thought patterns, but ultimately there are thoughts about yourself that are being felt emotionally.

Inquiry is about expressing and "releasing" self-referential thoughts by bringing them up to the limelight and seeing they aren't really representing something you can find in your experience. Relief is felt because the thoughts aren't aren't appearing anymore, or they aren't believed in or focused on anymore.

Expressing/writing/observing thoughts helps transform the thought you're feeling into something more productive and aligned with what you want, which feels better.

Emotions/feelings are an intelligence which guides you towards what you want, pretty indiscriminately. Thought creates perception of what you want which feels pleasant (emotion guides you towards it). Thought creates perception of what you don't want which feels unpleasant (emotion guides you away from it).

The emotion is how the situation feels. Example, there can't be anxiety of work tomorrow without work tomorrow, and so anxiety is how the perception of work tomorrow feels. The assumption that thoughts are describing things creates intelligent guidance away from that situation in the form of emotions, but the error is that the thoughts aren't actually describing a situation at all. The intelligence in emotions doesn't really care about this, it just cares about what you believe you are perceiving, and so it sees thoughts as an object which needs to be dealt with, and so aversion (intelligent emotional guidance) is felt in accordance with that imagination. If you believe there is a bear in the closet, you will feel like there is a bear in the closet, and your emotional intelligence will bend to that assumption until it is realized that it is merely an assumption.
